[[Category:Books by subject]]

{{Persian/top}}

In [[Persian/Lesson 1|lesson 1]], you learned some greetings, the first nine letters of the Persian Alphabet, and how to spell several words with those letters from right to left.  You also learned that short vowels are usually not written, and that many letters change their shape depending on whether they connect with letters before or after them.

In this lesson, you will learn more formal greetings, the next eleven Persian letters and syllable stress.

== Dialogue: ‹'''hâl'''-e šo'''mâ''' ce'''tor''' e?› ==
Arash sees Peyman:

{{Persian/dialogue-top}}
{{Persian/dialogue| | Arash | |sa'''lâm''', '''â'''qâ-ye '''pey'''mân. '''hâl'''-e šo'''mâ''' ce'''tor''' e?|Hello, Mr. Peyman.  How are you?| audio=<!-- fa-سلام، آقای پیمان. حال شما چطور است؟.ogg -->}}
{{Persian/dialogue| | Peyman | |sa'''lâm''', '''â'''raš. '''xub'''am, '''mer'''si. šo'''mâ''' ce'''tor'''in?|Hello Arash. I am well, thank you.  How are you?| audio=<!--fa-سلام، آرش .خوبم، مرسی. شما چطورین؟.ogg -->}}
{{Persian/dialogue| | Arash | |man '''xub'''am, '''mer'''si.  xo'''dâ''' hâ'''fez''', '''â'''qâ-ye '''pey'''mân.|I am well, thanks.  Goodbye, Mr. Peyman!| audio=<!--fa-من خوبم، مرسی. خدا حافظ، آقای پیمان.ogg-->}}
{{Persian/dialogue| | Peyman | |xo'''dâ''' hâ'''fez'''.|Goodbye.| audio=<!-- fa-خدا حافظ.ogg -->}}
|}

'''Explanation'''
:Arash and Peyman are using a more formal style of speech typically used to show respect.  That is why they use the formal pronoun {{term-fa|شما|hide Arab=yes|šo'''mâ'''}} instead of the informal {{term-fa|تو|hide Arab=yes|tow}} used in [[Persian/Lesson 1|lesson 1]].

'''Vocabulary'''
{{Persian/vocab-list|hide Arab=yes
|آقا|'''â'''qâ|/ˈɒːɣɒː/|Mr.|
|حال|'''hâl'''|/ˈhɒːl/|health|
|شما|šo'''mâ'''|/ʃoˈmɒː/|you|(formal, shows speaker's respect for listener)
|چطور|ce'''tor'''|/t͡ʃeˈtoɾ/|how|<small>(the endings ‹e› and ‹-in› will be explained in [[Persian/Lesson 5|Lesson 5]])</small>
|خدا حافظ|xo'''dâ''' hâ'''fez'''|/xoˈdɒː hɒːˈfez/|May God keep you|(similar to the literal meaning of “goodbye”, i.e. “May God be with you”)
}}

{{Persian linguistics note
| Culture Point: Titles
| Titles like {{term-fa|آقا|âqâ|sir, Mr.}} are used before or after the first name, before or after a last name, or before or after both names. In the dialogue above, it is used before the first name {{Persian/text|پيمان|peyman}}.

The feminine version of {{Persian/text|آقا|âqâ|sir, Mr.}} is {{Persian/text|آغا|âqâ|madam, Miss}}.  The two words are pronounced the same way and are sometimes confused for each other as a misspelling, but {{Persian/text|آقا}} is the proper spelling for use with male names and {{Persian/text|آغا}} for female names.

Family names are a relatively new aspect of Persian culture, having been introduced in Iran in 1912.
}}

{{Persian linguistics note
| Syllable stress
| In most Persian words, the stress falls on the last syllable of the stem.

For example, in the following words from the dialogue, the stress is on the last syllable:
* ‹šo'''mâ'''›
* ‹ce'''tor'''›
* ‹mam'''nun'''›
* ‹xo'''dâ'''›
* ‹hâ'''fez'''›

When suffixes and [[w:Clitic|enclitics]] are added to Persian words and word stems, the stress usually does not move:
* ‹ce'''tor'''› + ‹-in› → ‹ce'''tor'''in›
* ‹'''hast'''› + ‹-am› → ‹'''hast'''am›
* ‹'''hâl'''› + ‹-e› → ‹'''hâl'''-e›

A few prefixes and suffixes are stressed.  Those details will be explained in the lessons for those suffixes and prefixes.

A limited set of Persian words (interjections, conjunctions and vocatives), however, has the stress on the first syllable:
* ‹'''mer'''si› — First syllable is stressed when used as in the conversation above, "Thanks!"
* ‹'''â'''qâ-ye› — First syllable is stressed when addressing someone by title as in the conversation above, but not when talking with someone else about ‹â'''qâ'''-ye› so-and-so.
* ‹'''â'''raš› — First syllable is stressed when addressing Arash as in the conversation above, but the last syllable is stressed ‹â'''raš'''› when talking about him.
* ‹'''pey'''mân› — First syllable is stressed when addressing Peyman as in the conversation above, but the last syllable is stressed ‹pey'''man'''› when talking with someone else about him.
}}

<span id="د" /><span id="ذ" />

== د ‹dâl›, ذ ‹zâl› ==
{| align=right class=PrettyTextBox style="background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249); margin-bottom: 1em;" dir=rtl
| colspan=2 | ← <small>(read from right to left)</small> ←
|- style="font-size:200%; font-family:{{Persian/fonts-simple}}; line-height:1.5em"
|  د || ذ
|-
| ‹dâl› || ‹zâl›
|}
The next two Persian letters, shown on the right, have the same basic form, but only second one has a dot.  Like <big>ا</big> ‹alef›, these two letters do '''not''' connect with the letter that follows them.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=&zwnj;د&zwnj;| Latn=dâl| audio=fa-د.ogg | key=does not connect with the following letter}}
The letter {{term-fa|د|dâl}} represents the /d/ sound.  It sits on the baseline and is written beginning at the top, ending at the bottom left. Its name sounds like the English word “doll”.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=داد| Latn=dâd| audio= fa-آب.ogg |د|d|ا|â|د|d}}
The Persian word {{term-fa|داد|dâd|(he/she/it) gave}} is shown on the right.  As shown, <big>د</big> does '''not''' join with the letter that follows it.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=&zwnj;ذ&zwnj;| Latn=zâl | key=does not connect with the following letter}}
The letter {{term-fa|ذ|zâl}} is one of the “foreign” letters in Persian.  In Arabic, it represents the consonant [[w:Voiced dental fricative|[ð]]], but Persian does not have that sound, so it is pronounced as the closest Persian sound.  Thus, <big>ذ</big> ‹zâl› is one of four Persian letters pronounced /z/.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=ذات|Latn=zât|ذ|z|ا|â|ت|t}}
As shown in {{term-fa|ذات|zât|essence}} on the right, the letter <big>ذ</big> also does '''not''' join with the letter that follows it.

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet= Arabic alphabet dal-dhal.png
|د|dâl|Daal-fina.svg|Lettre 8 dâl.jpg|Lettre 8.gif|ذ|zâl|DHaal-fina.svg|Lettre 9 ḏâl.jpg|Lettre 9 ḏâl.gif}}

<br style="clear:both" /><span id="ر" /><span id="ز" /><span id="ژ" />

== ر ‹re›, ز ‹ze›, ژ ‹že› ==
{| align=right class=PrettyTextBox style="background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249); margin-bottom: 1em;" dir=rtl
|- style="font-size:200%; font-family:{{Persian/fonts-simple}}; line-height:1.5em"
|  ر || ز || ژ
|-
| ‹re› || ‹ze› || ‹že›
|}
The next three Persian letters, also have the same basic form except for the dots.  They are all written with a tail that drops well below the baseline.  Like <big>ا</big> ‹alef›, <big>د</big> ‹dâl›, and <big>ذ</big> ‹zâl›, these three letters do '''not''' connect with the letter that follows them.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=&zwnj;ر&zwnj;|audio=fa-ر.ogg|Latn=re| key=does not connect with the following letter}}
The letter {{term-fa|ر|re}} is pronounced as [[w:Alveolar tap|[ɾ]]], that is, it is produced by striking the tongue against the roof of the mouth just behind the teeth, then expelling air over the middle of the tongue, similar to the ''r'' in the Scottish English pronunciation of ''f'''r'''ee'' or the ''tt'' in the American English and Australian English ''be'''tt'''er''. Between vowels, it is often [[w:Trill consonant|trilled]] like ''rr'' in the Spanish word ''[[wikt:perro#Spanish|pe'''rr'''o]]''.  Its name, ‹re›, sounds similar to a quick pronunciation of the English word "ray".

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=در|Latn=dar|د|d|ر|r| audio=fa-در.ogg }}
As shown below the word {{term-fa|در|dar|door}}, the letter <big>ر </big> does not join with the letter that follows it. 

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=چرا|Latn=cerâ|چ&zwj;|c|&zwj;ر|r|ا|â}}
<big>چ</big> followed by <big>ر</big> and <big>ا</big> spells the word {{term-fa|چرا|cerâ|why}}.  Recall that ‹e›, like other short vowels, is not usually written in Persian.

<br style="clear:both"/>
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=&zwnj;ز&zwnj;|audio=fa-ز.ogg|Latn=ze| key=does not connect with the following letter}}
The letter {{term-fa|ز|ze}} is the most common of the four ‹z› letters in Persian. 

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=رز| Latn=roz|ر|r|ز|z}}
The word {{term-fa|رز|roz|rose}} is shown on the right.  Recall that ‹o› is usually not spelled in Persian words.  Like <big>ر</big>, <big>ز </big> does not join with the letter that follows it. 

<br style="clear:both"/>
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=&zwnj;ژ&zwnj;| audio=fa-ژ.ogg |Latn=že| key=does not connect with the following letter}}
The letter {{term-fa|ژ|že}} is transcribed in [[w:Romanization of Persian#UniPers|UniPers]] and here as ‹ž› and is pronounced as [[w:Voiced postalveolar fricative|[ʒ]]], i.e. like the "g" in "mira'''g'''e" or the ''s'' in ''mea'''s'''ure'' and ''Per'''s'''ian''. If you open your Persian-English dictionary at the letter <big>ژ</big> , you can see that it is not used in very many words. It occurs in many loanwords of French origin.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=ژخ|Latn=žax|ژ|ž|خ|x}}
As shown in the word {{term-fa| ژخ |zhakh|wart}}, <big>ژ </big> does not join with the letter that follows it. 

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet= Arabic alphabet ra-zay.png
|caption= Arabic examples.  Persian examples would be better here, probably a separate page to print out with letters to trace.
|ر|re|Raa-fina.svg|Lettre 10 râʾ.jpg|Lettre 10 râ'.gif|ز|ze|Zai-fina.svg|Lettre 11 zâī.jpg|Lettre 11 zây.gif|ژ|že|11a-Zhe.png|Jaa-individua.svg|Jaa-fina.svg}}

<br style="clear:both" /><span id="س" /><span id="ش" />

== س ‹sin›, ش ‹šin› ==
{| align=right cellspacing=10 class=PrettyTextBox style="background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249); -moz-border-radius: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em;" dir="RTL"
|- style="font-size:200%; font-family:{{Persian/fonts-simple}}; line-height:1.5em"
|  س || ش
|-
| ‹sin› || ‹šin›
|}
The next two Persian letters have the same shape, but one of them has no dots and the other has three.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=س| audio=fa-س.ogg| Latn=sin}}
The letter {{term-fa|س|sin}} is the usual Persian letter for /s/.  Its name sounds like the English word "seen".

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=سر|Latn=sar| س&zwj; |s| &zwj;ر |r}}
As shown in the word {{term-fa|سر|sar|head}} on the right, the letter <big>س</big> joins with the letter that follows it.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=ش| audio=fa-ش.ogg|Latn=šin}}
The letter {{term-fa|ش|šin}} is pronounced as [[w:Voiceless postalveolar fricative|[ʃ]]], that is, like "sh" in English.  It is transcribed in [[w:Romanization of Persian#UniPers|UniPers]] as ‹š›, but in other literature it may be transcribed as ''sh'', ''sch'', ''ʃ'', or ''ş''.  Its name sounds like the English word “sheen”.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=شب| Latn=šab | ش&zwj; |š| &zwj;ب|b}}
As shown in the word {{term-fa|شب|šab|evening}}, the letter <big>ش</big> joins with the letter that follows it.

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=Arabic alphabet sin-shin.png
|س|sin|Siin-individua.svg|Lettre 12 sīn.jpg|Lettre 12 sīn.gif|ش|šin|SHiin-individua.svg|Lettre 13 šīn.jpg|Lettre 13 šîn.gif}} 

<br style="clear:both" /><span id="ص" /><span id="ض" />

== ص ‹sâd›, ض ‹zâd› ==
{| align=right class=PrettyTextBox style="background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249); margin-bottom: 1em;" dir=rtl
|- style="font-size:200%; font-family:Tahoma;"
| ص || ض </font>
|-
| ‹sâd› || ‹zâd›
|}
The next two Persian letters have the same shape, but only one has a dot.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=ص|Latn=sâd| audio=fa-ص.ogg}}
The letter {{term-fa|ص|sâd}} is the third Persian letter for the sound /s/.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=صد|Latn=sad| ص&zwj; |s| &zwj;د |d}}
As shown in the word {{term-fa|صد|sad|hundred}}, on the right, the letter <big>ص</big> joins with the letter that follows it.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=ض| audio=fa-ض.ogg|Latn=zâd}}
The letter {{term-fa|ض|zâd}} is another Persian letter for the sound /z/.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/Connecting letters box | Arab=ضد|Latn=zed| ض&zwj; |z| &zwj;د |d}}
As shown in the word {{term-fa|ضد|zed|opposite}} on the right, the letter <big> ض </big> joins with the letter that follows it.

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=Arabic alphabet sad-dad.png
