{{Persian/top}}

In [[Persian/Lesson 1|lessons 1]] and [[Persian/Lesson 2|2]], you learned some greetings, the first fourteen letters of the Persian Alphabet, and how to spell several words with those letters.  You also learned syllable stress in Persian words.

In this lesson, you will learn more about casual and formal speech, the next nine Persian letters, and more about short vowels in Persian.

== Dialogue: ‹'''sobh''' be'''xeyr'''› ==
Hassan drops by to see his good friend Mohamad:

{{Persian/dialogue-top}}
{{Persian/dialogue| <!-- حسن --> | Hassan |<!--صبح بخیر، ممد!-->|sobh be'''xeyr''', '''ma'''mad!|Good morning, Mamad!| audio=}}
{{Persian/dialogue| <!-- محمد --> | Mohamad |<!--صبح بخیر، حسنی. حالت چطور است؟-->|sobh be'''xeyr''', hasani. '''hâl'''et ce'''tor''' e?|Good morning, Hassani. How’s your health?| audio=}}
{{Persian/dialogue| <!-- حسن --> | Hassan |<!--بد نیستم، مرسی. و تو؟-->|bad '''ni'''stam, '''mer'''si. va to?|Not bad, thanks. And you?| audio=}}
{{Persian/dialogue| <!-- محمد --> | Mohamad |<!--من خیلی خوب است.-->|man '''xey'''li '''xub'''am.|I'm very good.| audio=}}
|}

'''Explanation'''
:Mohamad and Hassan are using a very casual style of speech because they are close friends.  “Mamad” is a common nickname for people named Mohamad.  “Hassani” is a common nickname for people named “Hassan”.

'''Vocabulary'''
{{Persian/vocab-list|hide Arab=yes
|صبح بخیر|sobh be'''xeyr'''|/sobh beˈxejɾ/|Good morning|
|حالت|'''hâl'''et|/ˈhɒːlet/|your health|(informal)
|بد|bad|/bæd/|bad|similar meaning and pronunciation as the English word
|نیستم|'''nist'''am|/ˈniːstæm/|(I) am not|
|و|va, o|/væ/, /o/|and|
|خیلی|'''xey'''li||very|
}}

{{Persian/linguistics note
| Familiarity and formality
| In any language, speakers use various levels of formality in various social settings. For example, an English speaker in a formal setting may use proper grammar, pronounce ''-ing'' clearly (i.e., so that "walking" does not sound like "walkin'"), may choose formal or technical words (e.g. ''sodium chloride'' rather than ''salt'' and ''child'' rather than ''kid''), and refrain from saying ''ain't'', but the same person could violate some or all of those rules in an informal setting.

In Persian, several speech patterns are used to raise or lower the level of formality.  One general rule in the Persian formality system is that referring to an individual with a plural pronoun and/or plural verb indicates respect for that individual.  In polite Persian conversations, it is therefore customary to use the plural pronoun {{Persian/text|شما|šomâ}} to when speaking with a superior or someone whom one has just met, and to use the singular pronoun {{Persian/text|تو|to}} only when talking to friends, family members, and the like.

}}

<span id="ع" /><span id="غ" />

== ع ‹’eyn›,  غ ‹qeyn› ==
{| align=right cellspacing=10 class=PrettyTextBox style="background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249); -moz-border-radius: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em;" dir="RTL"
| colspan=2 | ← <small>(read from right to left)</small> ←
|- style="font-size:200%; font-family:Tahoma;"
| ع || غ
|-
| dir=ltr | ‹’eyn› || ‹qeyn›
|}
The next two letters have the same form except only one has a dot over it. The bottom hook in these letters is a tail that only appears in isolated and final position.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=ع|audio=fa-ع.ogg|Latn=’eyn}}
The Persian letter {{term-fa|ﻉ|’eyn}} represents the sound [[w:Glottal stop|[ʔ]]], i.e. the glottal stop in the middle of “uh-oh” in English.  Traditionally, as well as in [[w:Romanization of Persian#UniPers|UniPers]] it is transcribed as ‹’›.   Its name sounds something like the English word “main”, but beginning with a glottal stop instead of an ''m''.  The top loop sits on the baseline.  When it is the last (or only) letter in a word, its lower loop hangs below the baseline.  When another letter follows it, it has a different form.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=رعد|audio=fa-ع.ogg|Latn=ra'd|ر |r|ع&zwj;|’|&zwj;د|d}}
As shown on the right, the letter <big>ﻉ</big> ‹’eyn› combines with the letter that follows it, e.g. with <big>د</big> in the word {{term-fa|رعد|ra’d|thunder}}.  

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=غ|audio=fa-غ.ogg|Latn=qeyn}}
The Persian letter {{term-fa|غ|qeyn}} represents the sound [[w:Voiced velar fricative|[ɣ]]], that is, it is produced by placing the back part of the tongue against the soft palate and vibrating the vocal cords while pushing air from the lungs over the middle of the tongue.

The top loop sits on the baseline.  When it is the last (or only) letter in a word, its lower loop hangs below the baseline.  When another letter follows it, it has a different form.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=باغ|audio=Fa-باغ.ogg |Latn=bâq|ب&zwj;|b|&zwj;ا|â|غ|q}}
As shown on the right, the letter <big>ﻍ</big> ‹qeyn› is used to spell {{term-fa|باغ|bâq|garden}}.

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=Arabic alphabet ayn-ghayn.png
|ع|'eyn|Ain-individua.svg|Lettre 18 ʿayn.jpg|Lettre 18 'ayn.gif|غ|qeyn|GHain-individua.svg|Lettre 19 ġayn.jpg|Lettre 19 ġayn.gif}} 

