== ف ‹fe›, ق ‹qaf› ==

{| align=right cellspacing=10 class=PrettyTextBox style="background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249); -moz-border-radius: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em;" dir="RTL"
|- style="font-size:200%; font-family:Tahoma;"
| ف ||  ق
|-
| ‹fe› || ‹qaf›
|}
The next two letters are shown on the right.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=ف|audio=fa-ف.ogg|Latn=fe}}
The Persian letter {{term-fa|ف|fe}} sits on the baseline.  Its name sounds like a quick pronunciation of "Faye".

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=فردا|Latn=fardâ|ف&zwj;|f|&zwj;ر|r|د|d|ا|â}}
As shown on the right, the letter <big>ف</big> ‹fe› combines with the letter that follows it, e.g. as the first letter in the word {{term-fa|فردا|fardâ|tomorrow}}.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=ق|audio=fa-ق.ogg|Latn=qaf}}
The Persian letter {{term-fa|ق|qaf}} is pronounced like <big>غ</big> ‹qeyn›, i.e. like [[w:Voiced velar fricative|[ɣ]]].  The small loop sits on the baseline and the tail, when present, hangs below the baseline.  Like other Persian letters with tails, the tail is only written when no other letter follows.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=آقا|Latn=âqâ|آ |â|ق&zwj;|q|&zwj;ا|â}}
As shown on the right, the letter <big>ﻕ</big> ‹qaf› combines with the letter that follows, as in {{term-fa|آقا|âqâ|Mr., sir, gentleman}}.

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=Arabic alphabet fa-qaf.png
|ف|fe|Faa-individua.svg|Lettre 20 fâʾ.jpg|Lettre 20 fâ.gif|ق|qaf|Qaaf-individua.svg|Lettre 21 qâf.jpg|Lettre 21 qâf.gif}} 

<br style="clear:both" /><span id="ک" /><span id="گ" />

== ک ‹kaf› and گ ‹gaf› ==

{| align=right cellspacing=10 class=PrettyTextBox style="background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249); -moz-border-radius: 1em; margin-bottom: 1em;" dir="RTL"
|- style="font-size:200%; font-family:Tahoma;"
| ک || گ
|-
| ‹kaf› || ‹gaf›
|} 

The next two letters are shown on the right.

<br style="clear:both"/>
{{Persian/connecting letters box |  Arab=ک| Latn=kaf| audio =fa-ک.ogg}}
The Persian letter {{term-fa|ک|kaf}} sits on the baseline.  The slash on top (&nbsp;<sup>/</sup>&nbsp;) is written after the connected strokes of the word, along with the dots in any of the word’s dotted letters.  Its name sounds a bit like the English word “cough”.

<br style="clear:both"/>
{{Persian/connecting letters box |  Arab=کتاب| Latn=ke'''tâb'''| audio =fa-سگ.ogg |ک&zwj;|k|&zwj;ت&zwj;|t|&zwj;ا|â|ب|b}}
As shown on the right, the letter <big>ک</big> combines with the letter that follows it, e.g. as the first letter in the word {{term-fa|کتاب|ketâb|book}}.

<br style="clear:both"/>
{{Persian/connecting letters box |  Arab=گ| Latn=gaf| audio =fa-گ.ogg }}

The Persian letter {{term-fa|گ|gaf}} sits on the baseline.  The two slashes on top (&nbsp;<sup>//</sup>&nbsp;) are written after the connected strokes of the word, along with the dots in any of the word’s dotted letters.

<br style="clear:both"/>
{{Persian/connecting letters box |  Arab=بزرگ| Latn=bozorg| audio =fa-بزرگ.ogg |ب&zwj;|b|&zwj;ز|z|ر|r|گ|g}}
As shown on the right, the letter <big>گ</big> is used in the word {{term-fa|بزرگ|bozorg|big}}.

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=Arabic alphabet kaf.png
|ک|kaf|Kahah-individua.svg|22b-Persisches Kaf.png||گ|gaf|Gaaf-individua.svg|22a-Gaf.png|Gaf.svg}} 

<br style="clear:both" /><span id="ل" />

==ل ‹lâm›==
{{Persian/connecting letters box|Arab=ل|Latn=lâm}}
The letter {{term-fa|ل|lâm}} sits on the baseline and connects with the letter that follows it.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=گل|Latn=gol|گ&zwj;|g|&zwj;ل|l}}
<big>ل</big> is the last letter in {{term-fa|گل|gol|flower}}.

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=Arabic alphabet lam.png
|ل|lâm|Laam-individua.svg|Lettre 23 lâm.jpg|Lettre 23 lâm.gif}}

<br style="clear:both" /><span id="م" />

== م ‹mim› ==
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=م|audio=fa-م.ogg|Latn=mim}}

The Persian letter <big>م</big> is pronounced as /m/.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box| Arab=اسم|ا|audio=fa-اسم.ogg|Latn=esm|e|س&zwj;|s|&zwj;م|m}}
The Persian word {{term-fa|اسم|esm|name}}, shown on the right, is an example of an initial alef without a “hat” ( <big> ا </big> ) used to indicate that the word begins with a short vowel, in this case, with ‹e›.

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=
|م|mim|Miim-individua.svg|Lettre 24 mīm.jpg|Lettre 24 mîm.gif}} 

<br style="clear:both" /><span id="ن" />

== ن ‹nun› ==
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=ن|Latn=nun|audio=fa-ن.ogg}}
The name of this letter "nun" is pronounced rhyming with "noon" and not "nun". Note the difference between <font size="5" face="Tahoma">ن</font> nun and <font size="5" face="Tahoma">ﺏ</font> be, in be the dot is below the curve and in nun it is above. The shape of nun is also narrower than the "be, pe, se, te" group of letters.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=نان|Latn=nun|ن&zwj;|n|&zwj;ا|â|ن|n}}
The Persian word {{term-fa|نان|nun|bread}} is shown on the right.  Note that the written form uses {{Persian/text|ا|â}}, indicating that the word should be pronounced as ‹nân›, but in standard Persian, {{Persian/text|ان|ân}} is usually pronounced ‹un›, including the word {{term-fa|آن|un|that}}.

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=
|ن|nun|Nuun-individua.svg|Lettre 25 nūn.jpg|Lettre 25 nūn.gif}}

