<span id="و" />

== و ‹vâv› ==
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=&zwnj;و|Latn=vâv|audio=fa-و.ogg| key=does not connect with the following letter}}
The letter و does '''not''' connect with the following letter.  It is pronounced in different ways, depending on the word: ‹v›, ‹u›, or ‹o›.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab= آواز |Latn=âvâz|آ|â|و|v|ا|â|ز|z}}
The word {{term-fa|آواز|âvâz|voice, song|IPA=/ɒːˈvɒːz/}} is shown on the right, demonstrating that <big>و</big> ‹vâv› is pronounced as the consonant ‹v› in some words.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab= چوب |Latn=cub| چ&zwj;|c|&zwj;و|u|ب|b}}
The word {{term-fa| چوب |cub|wood|IPA=/tʃuːb/}} is shown on the right, demonstrating that <big>و</big> ‹vâv› is pronounced as the long vowel ‹u› in some words.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab= اوت |Latn=ut| ا |-<!-- no sound -->|و|u|ت|t}}
The long vowel sound ‹u› may also occur at the beginning of a word, in which case it is spelled with initial <big>او</big>, as demonstrated on the right in {{term-fa|اوت|ut|August}}. 

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab= تو |Latn=to| ت&zwj;|t|&zwj;و|o}}
Some Persian words that were originally pronounced with the long vowel sound ‹u› are pronounced today with the sound ‹o›, but their spelling has not changed.  So <big>و</big> sometimes represents the sound ‹o› in Modern Persian:
* {{term-fa|تو|to|you (informal)}}
* {{term-fa|دو|do|two}}

{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=
|و|vâv|Waau-individua.svg|Lettre 27 wâw.jpg|Lettre 27 wâw.gif}} 

<br style="clear:both" /><span id="ه" />

== ه ‹he› ==
{{Persian/connecting letters box| Arab=ه| Latn=he| audio= fa-ﻩ.ogg }}
The letter {{term-fa|ه|he}} is often pronounced like ‹h›, just like the Persian letter {{term-fa|ح|he}}.  To distinguish between them, a Persian speaker may specify {{Persian/text|ح}} by saying ‹he-ye jimi›, in reference to the similar form shared with {{Persian/text|ج|jim}}.  Or, because of the traditional arrangements of letters in chronograms, they may be distinguished as {{Persian/text|حاء حطّی|he-ye hotti}} for {{Persian/text|ح}} and {{Persian/text|هاء هوّز|he-ye havvaz}} for {{Persian/text|ه}}.

{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=جوجه|Latn= jojeh|ج&zwj;|j|&zwj;و|o|ج&zwj;|j|&zwj;ه|h}}
The connecting forms of <big>ه</big> ‹he› are shown on the right in a typical Persian style.  There are several variations, though, so you may run across any of the following:
* {{term-fa|راه|râh|road, path}}
* {{term-fa|جوجه|jojeh|chicken}}

At the end of a word, {{Persian/text|ه}} often is not pronounced as ‹h›, but just indicates that the word ends in the sound ‹e›: {{Persian/text|خانه|xâne|house}}
{{Persian/writing practice
|worksheet=
|ه|he|Haa-individua.svg|Lettre 26 hâʾ.jpg|Lettre 26 hâ'.gif}} 

{{Persian/linguistics note
| Duplicate Letters
| In Persian there is more than one letter available for some sounds because words imported from Arabic are spelled using their Arabic spelling, but with Persian pronunciation. So, there are three letters for ‹s›, four for ‹z›, two for ‹t›, two for ‹q›, two for ‹h›, and two for ‹'›. They are not all used equally, for example <big>ز</big> is more common than the other ‹z› letters.

* ‹s›:
** <big>س</big>
** <big>ص </big>, e.g. {{term-fa|صد|sad|hundred}}
** <big>ث</big>
* ‹z›:
** <big>ز</big>
** <big>ذ</big>
** <big>ظ</big>
** <big>ض</big>, e.g. {{term-fa|راضی|râzi|satisfied}}
* ‹t›:
** <big>ت</big>
** <big>ط</big>, e.g. {{term-fa|طور|towr|method}}
* ‹q›:
** <big>ق</big>, e.g. {{term-fa|آقا|âqâ|sir}}
** <big>غ</big>, e.g. {{term-fa|آغا|âqâ|madam}}
* ‹h›:
** <big>ه</big>
** <big>ح</big>
* <'>:
*: In Arabic, a symbol known as ''hamza'' (&nbsp;<big>ء</big>&nbsp;) is used to separate two vowels. This convention only used in Persian for words of Arabic origin.
** <big>ء</big>, e.g. {{term-fa|رأس|râ's|head}}
** <big>ع</big>, e.g. {{term-fa|رعد|ra'd|thunder}}
}}

<span id="ی" />

== ی ‹ye› ==
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=ی|audio=fa-ی.ogg|Latn=ye}}
The last Persian letter, {{term-fa|ى|ye}}, has a few different pronunciations: ‹y›, ‹i›, or ‹ey›. Its isolated and final forms vary significantly from its initial and medial forms:  It has a tail and no dots in the isolated and final forms, but it has two dots and no tail in the initial and medial forms,.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=یک|Latn=yek|ی&zwj;|y|&zwj;ک|k}}
In {{term-fa|یک|yek|one}}, <big>ی</big> as the first letter of the word is pronounced ‹y›.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=سیب|Latn=sib| س&zwj; |s|&zwj;ی&zwj;|i|&zwj;ب|b}}
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=ایران|Latn=irân|ا|-<!-- alef has no pronunciation here -->|ی&zwj;|i|&zwj;ر|r|ا|â|ن|n}}
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=این|Latn=in|ا|-<!-- alef has no pronunciation here -->|ی&zwj;|i|&zwj;ن|n}}
As the examples {{Persian/text|این|in|this}} and {{term-fa|سیب|sib|apple}} show on the right, <big>ی</big> as the second letter of the word is pronounced as ‹i›.

{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab= فارسی |Latn=fârsi|ف&zwj;|f|&zwj;ا|â|ر|r|س&zwj;|s|&zwj;ی|i}}
In {{term-fa|فارسی|fârsi|Persian (language)}}, <big>ی</big> as the last letter of the word is pronounced as ‹i›.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian linguistics note
| Vowels at the beginning of words
| 2=When a Persian word begins with any vowel sound, it is spelled with an initial <big>ا</big>.   If that initial sound is a short vowel, the specific vowel is not indicated, but if it is a long vowel, the corresponding long vowel letter is written (&nbsp;<big>ا</big> for ‹â›, <big>و</big> for ‹o›, or <big>ی</big> for ‹i›). So, <big>ا</big> is the first letter in Persian words that begin with a long ‹i› sound, such as {{term-fa|ایران|irân|Iran}} and {{term-fa|اين|in|this}}. 

Remember from [[Persian/Lesson 1#ا|lesson 1]], though, the long ‹â› sound at the beginning of a word is not spelled with two <big>ا</big> letters in a row, but with <big>آ</big>, ''alef madde''. 
}}

