==Ligatures==
Certain combinations of letters are written in a combined form known as a ligature.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=لا|Latn=lâ|ل&zwj;|l|&zwj;ا|â}}
When {{Persian/text|ل|lâm}} is followed by {{Persian/text|ا|alef}}, they combine to form the ligature {{Persian/text|لا|lâ}}, as shown on the right.

{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=سلام|Latn=salâm|س&zwj;|s|&zwj;ل&zwj;|l|&zwj;ا|â|م|m}}
The lâm-alef ligature appears in the greeting {{Persian/text|سلام|salâm}}.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box | Arab=ۀ|Latn=he-ye|ه&zwnj;|he|&zwnj;ی|ye}}
In an ezafe construction after a word ending in ‹he›, the <big>ی</big> is sometimes written in a small form over the <big>ه</big>, i.e. as {{Persian/text|ۀ|he-ye}}.  It looks like a hamze, and is considered such by some, but others consider this a ligature of <big>ه‌ی</big>.

==Diacritics==
Like the accent mark over the ''e'' in ''[[wikt:café|café]]'', Persian diacritics (symbols written above or below the letters) are not actual letters in the Persian alphabet.

* {{Persian/text|ّ |tašdid|strengthening}}

Tashdid is a mark that looks like a small, curly ''w'', placed above a consonant to double or strengthen it. It may be omitted, but is used in many situations for clarity.

=== {{Persian/text|ء|hamze}} ===
{| align=right class=PrettyTextBox style="background-color: rgb(249, 249, 249);" dir=rtl
|-
| colspan=2 dir=ltr | The diacritic ‹hamze›, isolated and over ‹he›:
|- style="font-size:200%; font-family:{{Persian/fonts-simple}}; line-height:1.5em"
| ء || هٔ
|-
| colspan=2 dir=ltr | {{Audio|fa-هٔ.ogg|‹’›, ‹ye›}}
|}
The symbol on the right is called {{Persian/text|همزه|hamze}}. It is never at the beginning of a word and has different pronunciations, depending on whether it is in a native Persian word or one borrowed from Arabic.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box|Arab=خانهٔ|Latn=xuneye| خ|x|ا|â|ن|n|هٔ|e-ye}}
In Persian words, hamze may be written over silent final ‹he› (&nbsp;<big>هٔ</big>&nbsp;), as shown on the right, to represent the sound ‹ye› in a construction called ‹ezâfe› that will be explained in [[Persian/Lesson 6|Lesson 6]].  The hamze for this purpose is usually left unwritten and is only added for extra clarity.  Rarely, it is used in the same way with words ending in <big>ی</big> (that is, <big>ئ</big>).

{| align=right
! Historically !! &nbsp; !! Modern
|-
| {{Persian/text|جملهٔ}} || || {{Persian/text|جمله‌ای|jomlei|a sentence}}
|-
| {{Persian/text|قهوهٔ رنگ}} || || {{Persian/text|قهوه‌ای رنگ|qahvei rang|brown}}
|-
| {{Persian/text|خستهٔ}} || || {{Persian/text|خسته‌ای|xaste i|you are tired}}
|-
| {{Persian/text|شیمیائی}} || || {{Persian/text|شیمیایی|šimiāi|chemical}}
|-
| {{Persian/text|بگوئید}} || || {{Persian/text|بگویید|beguid|say}}
|}
Historically, Persian words with the sounds ‹âi› or ‹ui› were written with a hamze (that is, with <big>ائی</big> or <big>وئی</big>) to show that the vowel sounds were separate, but today such words are usually written with a doubled <big>ی</big> (that is, ‹âi› is written as <big>ایی</big> and ‹ui› as <big>ویی</big>) instead.  Similarly, words ending with ‹ei› were once written as <big>هٔ</big>, but today that ending is written as <big>ه‌ای</big>.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box|Arab=ژوئن|Latn=žuan|ژ|ž|و|u|ئ&zwj;|-|&zwj;ن|n}}
As shown on the right, <big>ئـ</big> is used in some foreign words, like {{term-fa|ژوئن|žuan|June}} (from French ''[[wikt:juin#French|juin]]''), to show a transition between vowels.

<br style="clear:both" />
{| align=right
| أ ‹a’›/‹’a›
|
* {{Persian/text|متأسف|mota’assef|sorry}}
* {{Persian/text|تأسیس|ta’sis|foundation}}
|-
| ؤ ‹o’›
|
* {{Persian/text|مؤمن|mo’men|believer}}
* {{Persian/text|مسئول|mas’ul|responsible}}
|-
| ئو ‹’u›, ئـ ‹’›
|
* {{Persian/text|مسأله\مسئله|mas’ale|problem}}
|}
In words taken from Arabic, like the ones on the right, hamze may appear anywhere after the first letter of a word to represent a [[w:Glottal stop|glottal stop]] [ʔ], i.e. the same ‹’› sound that {{Persian/text|ع|’eyn}} represents.  Usually, though, <big>أ</big> is written without the hamze, e.g. {{Persian/text|متاسف|mota’assef}}, {{Persian/text|مساله|masale}}.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/connecting letters box|Arab=جزء|Latn=joz|ج&zwj;|j|&zwj;زء|z}}
At the end of an Arabic word, <big>ء</big> is usually silent and written by itself, e.g. {{Persian/text|جزء|joz|part}}.

Arabic loanwords ending with a final {{Persian/text|اء}} are sometimes still spelled that way, but the final hamze in such words is silent, so the hamze is usually omitted.  For example, {{Persian/text|ابتداء|ebtedâ|beginning}} is now usually written {{Persian/text|ابتدا}}.

=== Short vowel marks ===
In children's books and some other learning resources, short vowel are marked using the following symbols:
* {{Persian/text|َ}}, called {{Persian/text|زَبَر|zabar|above}} or  {{term-fa|فتحه‎‎|fatha|opening}}, is used to represent short ‹a›. E.g. {{term-fa|دَر|lemma=در|dar|door, at}}
* {{Persian/text|ِ}}, called {{Persian/text|زير|zir|below}} or {{term-fa|كَسره|kasra|breaking}}, is used to represent ‹e›.
* {{Persian/text|ُ }}, called {{Persian/text|پيش|piš|before}} or {{term-fa|ضَمّه|zamah}}, is used to represent ‹o›.

The short vowel diacritics may be doubled at the end of an Arabic loanword to indicate that the vowel is followed by ‹-n›, known as {{Persian/text|تنوين|tanvin|nunation}} (also, {{Persian/text|تنوين نصب |tanvin nasb|marking a consonant with tanvin}}). In Arabic, the signs indicate grammatical case endings: {{Persian/text|ـً|-un}} (nominative), {{Persian/text|ـٍ|-en}} (accusative), and {{Persian/text|ـٌ|-an}} (genitive).

A related mark is {{Persian/text|سُكون|sokun}}, also called {{Persian/text|جَزْم|jazm|amputation}}.  It is used to indicate the absence of a vowel and is written as a superscripted ''o'': {{Persian/text| ْ}}

