==''Ezâfe''==

{{Persian/translation |en=the door of the house|fa=در (دروازه) خانه |'''dar'''|door|
|در (دروازه)|e|of|
|خانه|xu'''ne'''|house|}}
An important part of Persian grammar is the handy little linking element called {{term-fa|اضافه|ezâfe|addition}}. It is used to extend a noun, pronoun, or noun phrase by adding an unstressed particle similar English “of”, followed by other words like adjectives, nouns, pronouns, and full phrases.

After a consonant, the ''ezâfe'' particle is pronounced as an unstressed ‹e› in standard Persian and is not usually written.  On the right, {{term-fa|در|dar|door}} is extended by the ''ezâfe'' particle and the noun {{term-fa|خانه|xune|house}}, making the Persian phrase {{Persian/text|در خانه|'''dar'''-e xu'''ne'''|the door of the house}}.  {{Persian/text|در|dar}} ends in a consonant, so the ''ezâfe'' particle is pronounced ‹e› and is not written.

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/translation |en=my house|fa=خانه (خانهٔ) من
|خانه|xu'''ne'''|house|
||ye|of|
|من|'''man'''|me|}}
After a vowel, the ''ezâfe'' particle is pronounced as unstressed ‹ye› and may be written as <big>ی</big> or, after a silent <big>ه</big>, it may be written as a miniature superscript <big>ی</big> that looks like a ''hamze'' diacritic, i.e. as <big>هٔ</big>.  Usually, though, it is only written after a vowel when extra clarity is wanted; otherwise it is often left unwritten.

{|
! Older texts
| {{Persian/text|صندلئ راحتی|sandaliye rāhati|easy chair}}
|-
! Modern texts
| {{Persian/text|صندلی راحتی}}
|}

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/translation |en=the woman’s scarf|fa=روسری زن
|روسری|rusa'''ri'''|scarf|
|ی|ye|of|
|زن|'''zan'''|woman|}}
When ''ezâfe'' extends one noun by adding another, it often indicates that the first noun’s referent belongs to the second one’s, as shown on the right in the Persian phrase {{Persian/text|روسری (چادر) زن|rusari-ye zan|the woman’s scarf}}.  In older texts, ''ezâfe'' after <big>ی</big> is often represented by a small superscripted <big>ی</big> that resembles ''hamze'' (&nbsp;<big>ء</big>&nbsp;), so you may see words like <big>{{Persian/text|روسرئ (چادر) زن}}</big>, but today, <big>{{Persian/text|یی}}</big> (and thus <big>{{Persian/text|روسری (چادر) زن}}</big>) is more common.

Colloquially, short forms are used even after vowels.
{{Persian/stub|Is this correct in all dialects?}}

Adding a noun with ''ezâfe'' is not only used for ownership.  It may indicate a family relationship:
* {{Persian/text|ناصر خسرو|nâ'''ser'''-e xos'''row'''|Nasir, [son] of Khusraw}}
* {{Persian/text|پدر و مادر من و شما|pe'''dar''' o mâ'''dar''' e '''man''' o šo'''mâ'''|mother and father of me and you}}

It may indicate composition or purpose:
* {{Persian/text|کاسه مسی|kâ'''se'''-ye '''messey'''|the bowl [made] of copper, the copper bowl}}
* {{Persian/text|آب زندگی|'''âb'''-e zende'''gi'''|the water of life}}

It may also used for [[w:Apposition|apposition]]:
* {{Persian/text|آقای پیمان|â'''qâ'''-ye pey'''mân'''|the gentleman Peyman, Mr. Peyman}}
* {{Persian/text|روز جمعه|'''ruz'''-e jom'''’e'''|the day Friday}}
* {{Persian/text|شهر تهران|'''šahr'''-e teh'''rân'''|the city of Tehran}}

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/translation |en=the big door |fa=در (دروازه) بزرک
| در|'''dar'''|door|
||e|[that is]|
|بزرک|bo'''zorg'''|big|}}
''Ezâfe'' is also used to add an adjective, as in the phrase {{Persian/text|در (دروازه) بزرک|'''dar''' e bo'''zorg'''|the big door}}, shown on the right.  The particle in such constructions is not usually translated into English as a separate word, but it may be thought of as “that is”.
* {{Persian/text|آب گرم|'''âb'''-e '''garm'''|water [that is] warm, warm water}}

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/translation | en=on (the face of) the wall|fa=بر روی دیوار
|بر|bar|on|
|روی|'''ruy'''|face|
||e|of|
|دیوار|di'''vâr'''|wall|}}
''Ezâfe'' is also used with certain nouns that have preposition-like meaning.  In the example on the right and the one below, the nouns {{term-fa|روی|ruy|face}} and {{term-fa|زیر|zir|underside}} are used like prepositions with the help of ''ezâfe'':
* {{Persian/text|از زیر میز|az '''zir'''-e '''miz'''|from the underside of the table}}

''Ezâfe'' is also used to add prepositional phrases, e.g. {{term-fa|بعد از|ba’d az ...|after ...}}:
* {{Persian/text|روز بعد از آن اتفاق|'''ruz'''-e '''ba’d''' az un ette'''fâq'''|the day after that accident}}

<br style="clear:both" />
{{Persian/translation |en=the big door of my house|width=50%|fa=در بزرک خانه من
|در|'''dar'''|door|
||e|[that is]|
|بزرک|bo'''zorg'''|big|
||e|of|
|خانه|xu'''ne'''|house|
||ye|of|
|من|'''man'''|me|}}
A noun phrase created with ''ezâfe'' may be extended with ''ezâfe'' again, as shown on the right.
<!--

The following examples are from Encyclopedia Iranica (http://www.iranica.com/newsite/index.isc?Article=http://www.iranica.com/newsite/articles/unicode/v9f2/v9f209.html).  They are too advanced for introduction at this level since we haven't yet covered infinitives or participles:

* Reduced relative clause: ‹dânešjuyân-e az orupâ bargašta› (“students back from Europe”)
* Nominalized verb phrase with infinitives and participles: {{Persian/text|کشتن شیر|koš'''tan'''-e '''šir'''|the killing of the lion}}, {{Persian/text|کشنه شدن شیر|'''koš'''te šo'''dan'''-e '''šir'''|the lion’s being killed)
* Figurative association: ‹nâma-râ ba-dast-e adab gereft› (“he took the letter with the hand of deference”, i.e., deferentially)
* Modification by infinitive: ‹âb-e xordan› (“drinking water”)

